00:28:45.060 --> 00:28:49.830
a perfect smoke point for – when you're
cooking spices. You don't want your oil to

00:28:49.830 --> 00:28:55.950
be too hot, because if it's too hot, it's
going to burn the spice. And if you have grape

00:28:55.950 --> 00:29:00.609
seed oil, a lot of chefs is using grape seed
oil these days. Grape seed oil has the highest

00:29:00.609 --> 00:29:05.909
smoke point. So, you could be heating it up
much higher than you wanted to and you could

00:29:05.909 --> 00:29:12.379
burn your spice, okay? I like to use olive
oil because I think olive oil has a nice fruitiness

00:29:12.379 --> 00:29:18.809
which adds another layer of flavor to the
food. I do use geese (ph) sometimes, but if

00:29:18.809 --> 00:29:23.049
I do use geese (ph), I'll make sure that people
know that's got geese (ph) in it because of

00:29:23.049 --> 00:29:28.679
the animal fat. A lot of vegans don't like
it. I do use nut oils in the restaurants.

00:29:28.679 --> 00:29:34.549
I think nut oils are great flavoring, but
I use them more as finishing. I love peanut

00:29:34.549 --> 00:29:39.419
oil but again, because of the allergies, I
tend not to use as much. In my own cooking

00:29:39.419 --> 00:29:44.820
at home, I use a lot of peanut oil. But I
think you could have a bunch of oils and you

00:29:44.820 --> 00:29:59.979
could choose as many oils as you want, but
you got to be careful on how you use them.

00:29:59.979 --> 00:30:07.619
So, I'm going to season this with salt. Whenever
you season with salt any meat, you want to

00:30:07.619 --> 00:30:11.719
let it set for a few minutes, like, I'd say,
five or ten minutes because it helps with

00:30:11.719 --> 00:30:21.389
the crust on the outside, it absorbs the salt
going to the meat. Okay?

00:30:21.389 --> 00:30:24.840
And when you have a spiced crust from the
outside, you want to be careful that your

00:30:24.840 --> 00:30:29.739
pan doesn't get too hot. You know, sometimes
when you do steaks, you want the oil to be

00:30:29.739 --> 00:30:35.859
really hot so you can sear it. But if you
have the oil too hot for this, you are going

00:30:35.859 --> 00:30:52.690
to burn the spice and make it bitter. You
know, our sauce is almost done, so I'm going

00:30:52.690 --> 00:31:08.999
to finish it up with some mint. You know,
cooking with spices can be so much of fun

00:31:08.999 --> 00:31:14.779
and make things so interesting that, you know,
most people don't realize that by adding something

00:31:14.779 --> 00:31:25.719
really, really simple to a dish, it changes
the whole complexity of the dish. Another

00:31:25.719 --> 00:31:38.469
thing that we--we chefs always do is we like
to--we like to taste as we cook because you

00:31:38.469 --> 00:31:48.940
are building flavors in there. And the other
thing that you want to put is, you know, put

00:31:48.940 --> 00:32:07.789
a little bit of jaggery or brown sugar, you
know, to balance out the acidity. Now, if

00:32:07.789 --> 00:32:13.210
this was a bigger piece of meat, I would most
definitely put it in the oven. This is very

00:32:13.210 --> 00:32:19.370
small; you can do it in stove top if you have
to. And there's another thing that we do in

00:32:19.370 --> 00:32:23.389
the restaurant is, when we are cooking a piece
of meat or fish we add a little bit of butter

00:32:23.389 --> 00:32:44.729
to the pan and then we baste it. And that
helps with the flavor as well as... So, as

00:32:44.729 --> 00:32:47.859
this cooks, if, you know, the longer you let
this cook the more thick it's going to get,

00:32:47.859 --> 00:32:56.440
the chickpeas. And you want it nice and thick
because it just, you know, the fattiness of

00:32:56.440 --> 00:33:51.859
the chickpeas comes through with acid and
the sweetness and the heat. And other thing

00:33:51.859 --> 00:33:56.359
we like to do, too, in the restaurant is we
like to add herbs to a pan when we are basting

00:33:56.359 --> 00:34:02.410
a piece of meat or fish because it just gives
it a little fresh flavor. You know, you could

00:34:02.410 --> 00:34:06.809
do the whole garlic, you can do sliced ginger,
you can do sliced shallots, you can do spice

00:34:06.809 --> 00:34:14.240
if you want. But it just makes it—makes
it more interesting. Now, I'm going to kind

00:34:14.240 --> 00:34:23.310
of rest this for a minute. And whenever you
do, if you're roasting meat, it's always a

00:34:23.310 --> 00:34:29.250
good practice to let the meat roast or let
the meat rest before you slice it, especially

00:34:29.250 --> 00:34:36.149
the medium rare or anything less than that.
Because if you-—you cook the meat and you

00:34:36.149 --> 00:34:41.120
go and slice it right away, what happens is,
as with protein as it cooks it tenses up,

00:34:41.120 --> 00:34:46.110
and all the juice from the inside comes to
the outside. And when you go and slice it,

00:34:46.110 --> 00:34:50.620
you got blood in the plate. But if you rest
it and you slice it, you got a beautiful pink

00:34:50.620 --> 00:35:13.010
in the middle and there's no juice on the
plate. And it's also very interesting because

00:35:13.010 --> 00:35:19.930
if you cook with spices there are very, very,
very many people who are very afraid of using

00:35:19.930 --> 00:35:26.190
spices in their food. And in my restaurant,
I get cooks who come in all the time and say,

00:35:26.190 --> 00:35:29.930
"Chef, I don't know how to cook with spices."
I say, "As long as you know how to cook, I

00:35:29.930 --> 00:35:36.700
can teach you." And if you've known the basics
of, you know, fresh spices, using oil, you

00:35:36.700 --> 00:35:43.900
know, taking care, balance, you know, don't
use too much, you can cook very well with

00:35:43.900 --> 00:35:50.990
spices. If you--you know, I have tasted restaurants
where the food has got way too much chili,

00:35:50.990 --> 00:35:55.600
or way too of garam masala, way too much of
something or the other. That's what kills

00:35:55.600 --> 00:36:02.090
the dish. But if you use it in limitation
and you follow the recipe and you follow the

00:36:02.090 --> 00:36:07.770
cooking technique, your dish can come out
perfectly every single time, you know. There's

00:36:07.770 --> 00:36:12.590
nothing that's-—I mean, you know, what I
did here is not what you guys do. This is

00:36:12.590 --> 00:36:17.220
not a rocket science. You just follow the
recipe. You know, I'm not discovering anything.

00:36:17.220 --> 00:36:23.370
I'm not doing new web pages or new search
engines or any of that kind of stuff. I'm

00:36:23.370 --> 00:36:29.040
just putting food together. And it got to
start from here, because if you don't have

00:36:29.040 --> 00:36:33.860
the passion, you know, you can—-like I can
tell when someone is cooking without passion

00:36:33.860 --> 00:36:40.310
in my kitchen. If a cook is unhappy, I can
see the product coming out. If I can go to

00:36:40.310 --> 00:36:45.390
someone's home and eat a meal, and I can tell
you if that meal was cooked with passion or

00:36:45.390 --> 00:36:51.020
not, or that person have a good day or a bad
day because it translates into the balance

00:36:51.020 --> 00:36:55.550
of the salt, the balance of the heat. It could
be the most simplest dish that they could

00:36:55.550 --> 00:37:00.090
be making. It doesn't-—like when, you know,
my friends who like to invite me over to eat,

00:37:00.090 --> 00:37:04.310
and they try to make fancy. And I told them,
"Don't make fancy. Make what's close to your

00:37:04.310 --> 00:37:09.970
heart because that's going to be good every
single time." And if that passion translates

00:37:09.970 --> 00:37:16.470
into what you do and you eat it, you get that
joy. And with food, that's all it's about.

00:37:16.470 --> 00:37:24.670
It's not about my ego, it's about the community.
It's about making you happy, making you enjoy

00:37:24.670 --> 00:37:33.980
these wonderful flavors and partake of this
meal.

