&gt;&gt; CARDOZ: You can use-—you know, there
are certain spices that you can use whole,

00:41:17.100 --> 00:41:21.780
okay? You can use cumin seed whole, you can
use black pepper roll but pull it out, you

00:41:21.780 --> 00:41:28.080
can use mustard seed whole, black cumin, fennel
seed; those you can use whole. Do you need

00:41:28.080 --> 00:41:33.030
to cook spices? I think you do. There are
certain spices that you can use without cooking,

00:41:33.030 --> 00:41:40.820
very limited, nutmeg, cinnamon, clove, black
pepper, fennel seed can be used uncooked.

00:41:40.820 --> 00:41:47.340
But you can extract the flavor of the spices.
You need heat for spices to extract the maximum

00:41:47.340 --> 00:41:51.820
flavor. So you can either do what I did and
start in with oil. That's one way you can

00:41:51.820 --> 00:41:54.660
do it. Or you can dry toast it...
&gt;&gt; Right, that's what...

00:41:54.660 --> 00:41:58.450
&gt;&gt; CARDOZ: Okay. All the other thing is you
can grind them like I did and cook them in

00:41:58.450 --> 00:42:02.590
oil. But if you grind them and cook them in
oil, then you only have a liquid with that.

00:42:02.590 --> 00:42:08.660
And in my book I mentioned, you know, best
ways to do it, but if you're going to grind

00:42:08.660 --> 00:42:14.010
it, you want to make sure that you have a
liquid to prevent the seed from actually burning.

00:42:14.010 --> 00:42:19.180
Because if your oil is too hot, if you have
water in there, you know, at 2:12 it's going

00:42:19.180 --> 00:42:25.190
to evaporate. So, you have--it's going to
bring the temperature down, okay. So, there

00:42:25.190 --> 00:42:29.850
are recipes in Indian cuisine where they start
off especially some bars where they start

00:42:29.850 --> 00:42:34.250
off with whole spices and they kind of toast
them in oil with onions and coconut and stuff,

00:42:34.250 --> 00:42:38.690
and then they take that and they grind it.
Now, in India, you have someone with a stone

00:42:38.690 --> 00:42:43.790
sitting over and grinding it. If I tell my
wife to do that, my bags will be outside of

00:42:43.790 --> 00:42:48.460
the house, you know. But you could use a blender.
There is one blender make which is called-—which

00:42:48.460 --> 00:42:49.910
one do we use at the restaurant?
&gt;&gt; Vita-Prep

00:42:49.910 --> 00:42:55.980
&gt;&gt; CARDOZ: Yes, it's called Vita-Prep which
is a great, great brand. Every restaurant

00:42:55.980 --> 00:43:01.820
kitchen uses it, and in that you can grind
spices with the oil. So, if you want that,

00:43:01.820 --> 00:43:04.310
it costs, well, I think, 500 bucks. But it's
a great blender.

00:43:04.310 --> 00:43:15.360
&gt;&gt; Where would you suggest getting fresh,
high-quality spices in the city?

00:43:15.360 --> 00:43:19.750
&gt;&gt; CARDOZ: OK, if you want to buy spices,
what you want to do is, and I'm not going

00:43:19.750 --> 00:43:23.830
to name any of the big stores because I don't
know if they advertise on the website or not,

00:43:23.830 --> 00:43:27.410
but I don't want to get into trouble, but
what you want to do is you want to go to an

00:43:27.410 --> 00:43:33.420
ethnic store. You want to go to a place that
has a fair amount of, say, if you go to an

00:43:33.420 --> 00:43:39.560
Indian store, a fair amount Indians and Pakistanis
going into buy them. Lexington Avenue has

00:43:39.560 --> 00:43:47.770
a fair amount of stores in New York. Every
major city in the country I know has an Indian

00:43:47.770 --> 00:43:52.730
spice store. In California; in New Jersey,
there are plenty of them; in Queens, there

00:43:52.730 --> 00:43:59.910
are plenty of them; in Manhattan, there are
tons of them. And, if you see--because if

00:43:59.910 --> 00:44:04.090
you know that if you're going to these stores
there is turnover and that there are people

00:44:04.090 --> 00:44:08.940
buying. And normally what happened in India
was that spices that spices grew one time

00:44:08.940 --> 00:44:13.260
a year. There were harvested once and they
were harvested for the whole year until the

00:44:13.260 --> 00:44:17.550
next year when they grew again. And you'd
use them for a year. What's happening now

00:44:17.550 --> 00:44:22.620
is because of packaging and we keep it for
a long time and it loses the flavor. So, if

00:44:22.620 --> 00:44:26.050
you go to a store that has high turnover,
that's the place to buy it from. You also

00:44:26.050 --> 00:44:29.880
want to buy small quantities, you know. You
can go to Edison, New Jersey, and you can

00:44:29.880 --> 00:44:35.290
buy 1 kilo or 2.5 pounds of coriander seed.
I don't know if they store any 2.5 pounds

00:44:35.290 --> 00:44:40.900
of coriander seed in my home, and I cook a
lot of Indian food. So you can buy it in ounces;

00:44:40.900 --> 00:44:46.310
you know, 1 ounce, 2 ounces. And they're pretty
good. You can even buy them online. There're

00:44:46.310 --> 00:44:52.560
tons of places that sell spices online; whole,
in small bags, 1 ounce, 2 ounces. So, that's

00:44:52.560 --> 00:44:56.810
what I would suggest. You know, I would not
go and buy everything because, you know, if

00:44:56.810 --> 00:45:02.770
you buy-—I have seen people buy half a pound
of, like, fenugreek. Fenugreek half a pound

00:45:02.770 --> 00:45:07.890
is a lot. You use half a pound of fenugreek
in anything and not going to eat it, it's

00:45:07.890 --> 00:45:12.020
going to be so bitter. The other, you know,
the other spice that they also have in this

00:45:12.020 --> 00:45:17.930
recipe, which I've forgot to use is azevetido.
It's a gum and it's used with beans. It's

00:45:17.930 --> 00:45:23.980
nice to put there with the chickpeas, which
I didn't. But you buy these containers which

00:45:23.980 --> 00:45:28.020
are that big. I have a container that big
at home which last me for a year. Because

00:45:28.020 --> 00:45:32.080
you use, like, an eight of a teaspoon when
you use it. Now, I had a new sous-chef in

00:45:32.080 --> 00:45:37.530
the restaurant who said, "I want to buy things
in bulk," and he bought six cases of azevetido,

00:45:37.530 --> 00:45:42.780
which I had to throw it because we could not
use them. It was so much. So, you want to

00:45:42.780 --> 00:45:46.140
be careful what you buy and how much you buy.
Like, you know, the other thing with—-if

00:45:46.140 --> 00:45:52.680
you buy green cardamom and if you use-—if
you grind green cardamom and you get green

00:45:52.680 --> 00:45:57.960
cardamom powder, okay, as soon as you grind
green cardamom, it has a half-life of 14 days.

00:45:57.960 --> 00:46:02.890
So, in 14 days it's going to lose half its
flavor. So just think about it, as it stays,

00:46:02.890 --> 00:46:14.010
even if it's ground, you're losing all these
wonderful oils that help you. Has everybody

00:46:14.010 --> 00:46:27.770
got everything?
&gt;&gt; So, for people who are just starting to

00:46:27.770 --> 00:46:33.050
cook Indian food, what three ingredients do
think they should add to their cupboard to

00:46:33.050 --> 00:46:34.700
start?
&gt;&gt; CARDOZ: The first three ingredients to

00:46:34.700 --> 00:46:44.570
buy are cumin, turmeric, and I'd say, coriander
seed. Because you have these three things

00:46:44.570 --> 00:46:48.500
you can do whatever—-you could do steaks.
Everybody has black-—I'm assuming everybody

00:46:48.500 --> 00:46:52.790
has pepper in the house, everybody has chili
flakes in the house, everybody has cinnamon

00:46:52.790 --> 00:47:01.730
at home, you know, and bay leaf. So, if you
have black pepper and coriander, you can make

00:47:01.730 --> 00:47:07.210
a curry out of it. If you have cumin and turmeric,
you can make a curry out of it. You can make,

00:47:07.210 --> 00:47:13.330
by varying these whole spices, you can make,
like, ten different curries just playing with

00:47:13.330 --> 00:47:24.450
the volume. But it's fun having fun with them.
It's not about being intimidated or, you know.

00:47:24.450 --> 00:47:30.291
It's not rocket science, absolutely not. It's
easy and fun and, you know. When I was—-when

00:47:30.291 --> 00:47:36.550
I went to school in Switzerland, I was dying
to eat Indian food but there was no Indian

00:47:36.550 --> 00:47:42.720
food in Switzerland where I was. I was in
Bluche, in the valley mountains. And the only

00:47:42.720 --> 00:47:49.880
spice they had was a curry spice that they
have which is absolutely nasty and disgusting.

00:47:49.880 --> 00:47:52.900
You know, if you're cooking, don't even go
and buy it because (a) you don't know when

00:47:52.900 --> 00:47:57.460
it was drowned, (b) you don't know what's
in there. And you know it's got some turmeric

00:47:57.460 --> 00:48:02.840
and it's got some fenugreek because can smell
it, but we had to use that and then it's just,

00:48:02.840 --> 00:48:07.620
you know. If you can make your own spice blend,
it's so easy, especially today. You know,

00:48:07.620 --> 00:48:11.280
you get a little spice blender like that,
and you can go anywhere and buy them. So,

00:48:11.280 --> 00:48:17.430
it's just not hard. It's pretty simple, you
know. I've made-—I've made curries with—using

00:48:17.430 --> 00:48:23.900
Bloody Marry mix at 2 o'clock in the morning
when I was a bachelor. You know, come back

00:48:23.900 --> 00:48:26.880
from a night out drinking and you want to
eat something and there's no food in the fridge

00:48:26.880 --> 00:48:30.350
but there's Bloody Mary mix and there's spices,
and there's potatoes. So, you make a potato

00:48:30.350 --> 00:48:34.620
curry and you eat it with rice, you know.
Or a chicken curry with Bloody Mary mix, but

00:48:34.620 --> 00:48:40.540
it tastes damn good, you know. But it's being
creative and using these spice mixes that

00:48:40.540 --> 00:48:43.720
you have and, you know, as long as you have
that, the neighbors are going to complain

00:48:43.720 --> 00:48:48.620
that you're grinding spices at 2 o'clock in
the morning. But who cares, you know? You're

00:48:48.620 --> 00:48:56.290
happy. Well, thank you.

